SIMPLE: sharpen
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sharpen
<hw>Sharp"en</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Sarpened</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Sharpening</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[See <er>Sharp</er>,
<pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <def>To make sharp.</def> Specifically:
<sd>(a)</sd> <def>To give a keen edge or fine point to; to make sharper;
<as>as, to <ex>sharpen</ex> an ax, or the teeth of a saw</as>.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>To render more quick or acute in perception; to make
more ready or ingenious.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The air . . . <qex>sharpened</qex> his visual ray⟦br⟧
To objects distant far.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He that wrestles with us strengthens our nerves and
<qex>sharpens</qex> our skill.</q> <rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <def>To make more eager; <as>as, to <ex>sharpen</ex>
men's desires</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Epicurean cooks⟦br⟧
<qex>Sharpen</qex> with cloyless sauce his appetite.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(d)</sd> <def>To make more pungent and intense; <as>as, to
<ex>sharpen</ex> a pain or disease</as>.</def> <sd>(e)</sd> <def>To make
biting, sarcastic, or severe.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Sharpen</xex> each
word.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>E. Smith.</au> <sd>(f)</sd> <def>To render more shrill
or piercing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Inclosures not only preserve sound, but increase and
<qex>sharpen</qex> it.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(g)</sd> <def>To make more tart or acid; to make sour; <as>as,
the rays of the sun <ex>sharpen</ex> vinegar</as>.</def> <sd>(h)</sd>
<fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>To raise, as a sound, by means of a sharp; to
apply a sharp to.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sharpen</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sharpen
<hw>Sharp"en</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To grow or become
sharp.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sharper</ent>⟦br⟧
